item.description:
Libanius to Priscus
Antioch, March [A.D.] 380
Yesterday morning as I was about to enter the lecture hall, I was stopped by a Christian student who asked me in a voice eager with malice, &ldquo;Have you heard about the Emperor Theodosius?&rdquo;
I cleared my throat ready to investigate the nature of this question, but he was too quick for me. &ldquo;He has been baptized a Christian.&rdquo;
I was non-committal. Nowadays, one never knows who is a secret agent.

When I was eleven years old, my life again changed abruptly. One morning in May I was doing lessons with Mardonius. I was reciting Hesiod and making a good many mistakes, when Gallus came into the room.
&ldquo;He&rsquo;s dead. The Bishop&rsquo;s dead. In the church. He died. Just like that!&rdquo;
Mardonius drew a cross on his chest; so did I. A moment later we were joined by clergy, officials, servants. Everyone was stunned, and alarmed, for it is a great event when the bishop of Constantinople dies, and who succeeds him is a matter of national importance.

&ldquo;Naturally the Caesar is concerned.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But without cause.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Without cause? You are a pupil of Maximus.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I am also a pupil of Ecebolius.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But he has not been with you for a year. Your brother feels that you are in need of a spiritual guide, especially now.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But Maximus is responsible.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Maximus is not a Christian. *Are you? *&rdquo; The question came at me like a stone from a sling. I stared a long moment at the blackrobed Deacon Aetius of Antioch.
